    The crash is caused by a use-after-free in destroy_list.                    
                                                                                
    The defective code is:                                                      
                                                                                
                                                                                
     for (Node *cur = head; cur != nullptr; cur = cur->next) {                  
         delete cur;                                                            
     }                                                                          
                                                                                
                                                                                
    At first glance this looks like it walks the list and deletes each node,    
    but the problem is the loop increment expression:                           
                                                                                
                                                                                
     cur = cur->next                                                            
                                                                                
                                                                                
    That expression runs after the loop body. But the loop body has already     
    done:                                                                       
                                                                                
                                                                                
     delete cur;                                                                
                                                                                
                                                                                
    So by the time the loop tries to evaluate cur->next, cur points to memory   
    that has already been deallocated.                                          
                                                                                
    That is the use of deallocated memory.                                      
                                                                                
    Step-by-step program state:                                                 
                                                                                
                                                                                
     Node *c = new Node{3, nullptr};                                            
     Node *b = new Node{2, c};                                                  
     Node *a = new Node{1, b};                                                  
     destroy_list(a);                                                           
                                                                                
                                                                                
    This creates the list:                                                      
                                                                                
                                                                                
     a -> b -> c -> nullptr                                                     
                                                                                
                                                                                
    More concretely:                                                            
                                                                                
                                                                                
     a: value = 1, next = b                                                     
     b: value = 2, next = c                                                     
     c: value = 3, next = nullptr                                               
                                                                                
                                                                                
    Then destroy_list(a) is called.                                             
                                                                                
    Inside destroy_list:                                                        
                                                                                
                                                                                
     static void destroy_list(Node *head) {                                     
         for (Node *cur = head; cur != nullptr; cur = cur->next) {              
             delete cur;                                                        
         }                                                                      
     }                                                                          
                                                                                
                                                                                
    Initially:                                                                  
                                                                                
                                                                                
     head = a                                                                   
     cur = head = a                                                             
                                                                                
                                                                                
    The condition succeeds:                                                     
                                                                                
                                                                                
     cur != nullptr                                                             
                                                                                
                                                                                
    Then the body runs:                                                         
                                                                                
                                                                                
     delete cur;                                                                
                                                                                
                                                                                
    This deletes the node a.                                                    
                                                                                
    However, cur itself still contains the old address of a. It is now a        
    dangling pointer. The memory at that address is no longer valid to read.    
                                                                                
    Then the for loop increment runs:                                           
                                                                                
                                                                                
     cur = cur->next;                                                           
                                                                                
                                                                                
    This attempts to read the next field from the already-deleted node a.       
                                                                                
    That is exactly what AddressSanitizer reports as:                           
                                                                                
                                                                                
     Use of deallocated memory                                                  
                                                                                
                                                                                
    The root cause is that destroy_list deletes the current node before saving  
    the pointer to the next node.                                               
                                                                                
    A minimal local fix is to save cur->next before deleting cur:               
                                                                                
                                                                                
     static void destroy_list(Node *head) {                                     
         Node *cur = head;                                                      
         while (cur != nullptr) {                                               
             Node *next = cur->next;                                            
             delete cur;                                                        
             cur = next;                                                        
         }                                                                      
     }                                                                          
                                                                                
                                                                                
    Or equivalently:                                                            
                                                                                
                                                                                
     static void destroy_list(Node *head) {                                     
         for (Node *cur = head; cur != nullptr; ) {                             
             Node *next = cur->next;                                            
             delete cur;                                                        
             cur = next;                                                        
         }                                                                      
     }                                                                          
                                                                                
                                                                                
    The important rule is:                                                      
                                                                                
                                                                                
     Node *next = cur->next; // read while cur is still valid                   
     delete cur;            // now cur is invalid                               
     cur = next;            // continue using saved pointer                     
                                                                                
                                                                                
    A more thorough root-cause fix would be to avoid manual ownership           
    management with raw pointers. The list owns its nodes, so that ownership    
    should be represented directly in the type system. For example, use         
    std::unique_ptr:                                                            
                                                                                
                                                                                
     #include <cstdio>                                                          
     #include <memory>                                                          
                                                                                
     struct Node {                                                              
         int value;                                                             
         std::unique_ptr<Node> next;                                            
                                                                                
         Node(int value, std::unique_ptr<Node> next = nullptr)                  
             : value(value), next(std::move(next)) {}                           
     };                                                                         
                                                                                
     int main() {                                                               
         auto a = std::make_unique<Node>(                                       
             1,                                                                 
             std::make_unique<Node>(                                            
                 2,                                                             
                 std::make_unique<Node>(3)                                      
             )                                                                  
         );                                                                     
                                                                                
         std::printf("done\n");                                                 
         return 0;                                                              
     }                                                                          
                                                                                
                                                                                
    With this version, no explicit destroy_list is needed. When a goes out of   
    scope, its std::unique_ptr<Node> automatically destroys the first node,     
    which destroys its next, and so on.                                         
                                                                                
    If this were part of a larger linked-list container, an even cleaner        
    design would be:                                                            
                                                                                
                                                                                
     #include <memory>                                                          
                                                                                
     struct Node {                                                              
         int value;                                                             
         std::unique_ptr<Node> next;                                            
                                                                                
         explicit Node(int value) : value(value), next(nullptr) {}              
     };                                                                         
                                                                                
     class List {                                                               
     public:                                                                    
         void push_front(int value) {                                           
             auto node = std::make_unique<Node>(value);                         
             node->next = std::move(head_);                                     
             head_ = std::move(node);                                           
         }                                                                      
                                                                                
     private:                                                                   
         std::unique_ptr<Node> head_;                                           
     };                                                                         
                                                                                
                                                                                
    This makes the ownership unambiguous: the list owns the head node, and      
    each node owns the next node.                                               
                                                                                
    Recommendation                                                              
                                                                                
    Minimal fix:                                                                
                                                                                
                                                                                
     static void destroy_list(Node *head) {                                     
         for (Node *cur = head; cur != nullptr; ) {                             
             Node *next = cur->next;                                            
             delete cur;                                                        
             cur = next;                                                        
         }                                                                      
     }                                                                          
                                                                                
                                                                                
    More robust fix: replace owning raw Node * pointers with                    
    std::unique_ptr<Node> so that node destruction is automatic and cannot      
    accidentally read through freed memory.                                     
                                                                                
